# Trivy ignore file for cowork's customer-facing Docker image.
#
# Each entry is a HIGH/CRITICAL CVE that we have triaged and accepted
# as residual risk. Every entry MUST cite:
#   1. The package and current Red Hat UBI 9 version.
#   2. Why no fix is applied (most commonly: no upstream patch yet).
#   3. Why the residual risk is acceptable in our threat model.
#
# This file is checked into the repo so the customer (and any auditor)
# can see exactly what we've ignored and why. Re-review on every base
# image bump — `docker pull registry.access.redhat.com/ubi9-minimal`
# then re-scan and remove any entry whose CVE is now patched in the
# new base.
#
# Last reviewed: 2026-05-07 against
#   registry.access.redhat.com/ubi9-minimal@sha256:
#     b9b10f42d7eba7ad4a6d5ef26b7d34fdc892b2ffe59b8d0372ec884008569eb6
# (Red Hat Enterprise Linux 9.7 "Plow")
#
# Threat model summary: cowork is a FastAPI HTTP server that listens on
# a single loopback port (default 26866). It does NOT terminate TLS, does
# NOT speak DTLS / WebRTC, does NOT speak Kerberos, and does NOT load
# arbitrary terminfo from network input. Every CVE below requires us to
# actively use a protocol stack we don't link or invoke. Scanner
# `objdump -T /opt/venv/bin/python | grep -iE 'gnutls|krb5'` returns
# empty, confirming no symbols are imported.

# gnutls 3.8.3-10.el9_7 — TLS / DTLS implementation. Pulled in
# transitively by ca-certificates / RPM tooling but never linked into
# cowork's Python process. The three DoS-class CVEs below all require
# the affected process to act as a DTLS server / RSA-PSK TLS server,
# which cowork never does (it serves plain HTTP on a loopback port).
# No upstream fix at scan time.
CVE-2026-33845
CVE-2026-33846
CVE-2026-42010

# krb5-libs 1.21.1-9.el9_7 — MIT Kerberos 5 client libraries. Present
# in UBI base; never invoked by cowork. The integer-underflow DoS
# requires the affected process to parse a malicious Kerberos ticket,
# which cowork has no code path to do. No upstream fix at scan time.
CVE-2026-40356
